text:
Park Avenue at N. W. corner of 93rd Street. The old residence, at the time shown occupied by the Ursuline Academy, is about to be demolished for a five-story fireproof building. (Note sign hung on the south well). It is shown on the 1879 map; it was probably built in that decade, and stood alone in the block for a number of years.

August 1911.

Gift of I.N. Phelps Stokes.

Park Avenue, at the N. W. corner of East 93rd Street, showing the Ursuline Academy prior to demolition for a 5 story building. This structure was originally built by General Scott.

August 1911

Underhill, photographer
Gift of Urbrock Collection
REPRODUCTION RIGHTS UNKNOWN

1172 Park Avenue at S.W. corner of 93rd Street, replacing four 5-story houses.

Summer 1926.

American Photo Service, Inc.,

Park Avenue, east side, north from 93rd Street. In the right foreground is seen the George Ehret mansion and garden recently sold and about to be demolished for the erection of an apartment house. The new apartment houses in the background, between 95th and 96th Streets, were both built since 1925. June 3, 1928.

P. L. Sperr, Photographer.

1197 Park Avenue, at S. E. corner of 94th Street, from S. W. corner of 93rd Street, showing Mansion and garden of the late George Ehret, brewer, which were sold that spring for three million dollars, and are about to be demolished. June 3, 1928.

P.L. Sperr, Photographer.

(2)

The same, taken from the sidewalk in front of 1180 Park Avenue, and showing the front door more clearly. June 3, 1928.

P.L. Sperr, Photographer.

(3)

The same, the old George Ehret mansion and garden, some fifty years old, which were sold that spring by his estate, are about to be demolished for an apartment house. The car making the turn down 94th Street to the east is an old T-model Ford.

P.L. Sperr, Photographer.
